'''Rheum''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|r|uː|m}}; from [[Greek language|Greek]]: [[wikt:ῥεῦμα|ῥεῦμα]] ''rheuma'' "a flowing, rheum"), also known as '''gound''', is thin mucus naturally discharged from the [[Human eye|eye]]s, [[Human nose|nose]], or [[mouth]] during sleep (cf. [[mucopurulent discharge]]).<ref>{{cite dictionary | title=Rheum (discharge)  | url=http://www.memidex.com/rheum+discharge | encyclopedia=Memidex Dictionary/Thesaurus | date=2009 | accessdate=2009-04-22}}</ref><ref name="amodio families.com">Amodio, Aimee.[http://health.families.com/blog/where-do-eye-boogers-come-from "Where Do Eye Boogers Come From?"], Families.com blog</ref><ref name=hiskey>Hiskey, Daven. [http://www.todayifoundout.com/index.php/2011/02/what-the-sleep-in-your-eyes-is/ "What the 'Sleep' In Your Eyes Is"], ''Today I Found Out'', 23 February 2011.</ref> Rheum dries and gathers as a crust in the corners of the eyes or the mouth, on the eyelids, or under the nose.<ref name=hiskey /> It is formed by a combination of [[mucus]] (in the case of the eyes, consisting of [[mucin]] discharged from the [[cornea]] or the [[Conjuctiva|conjunctiva]]), nasal mucus, [[blood cell]]s, [[Skin|skin cell]]s, or dust. Rheum from the eyes is particularly common. Dried rheum is commonly called '''sleep''',<ref>{{cite book|title=Shorter Oxford English Dictionary|year=2007|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-920687-2}}</ref> '''sleepy-seeds''',<ref name="partridge"/> '''sleepy buds''',<ref name="partridge">Eric Partridge, Paul Beale, ed., ''A Dictionary of Slang and Unconventional English'', 8th edition, 1984, ''s.v.''</ref> '''sleepy sand''', '''sleepers''', '''eye goop''', '''cheese''', '''eye boogers''', '''eye wappies''', or '''sleepy dust'''.<ref>http://www.nbcnews.com/health/body-odd/are-yours-crusty-or-wet-truth-behind-eye-boogers-ew-f1C6437167</ref>

When the individual is awake, blinking of the eyelid causes rheum to be washed away with tears via the [[nasolacrimal duct]]. The absence of this action during sleep, however, results in a small amount of dry rheum accumulating in corners of the eye, most notably in children.{{fact|date=April 2018}}

A number of conditions can increase the production of rheum in the eye.  In the case of [[allergic conjunctivitis]], the buildup of rheum can be considerable, many times preventing the sufferer from opening the eye upon waking without prior cleansing of the eye area.  The presence of [[pus]] in an instance of heavy rheum buildup can indicate [[dry eye]] or conjunctivitis, among other infections.{{fact|date=April 2018}}

In infants, the [[tear duct]]s (that drain the tears) occasionally fail to open, resulting in the overflow of tears onto the cheeks ([[Epiphora (medical)|epiphora]]) and rheum deposition on the surrounding skin.{{fact|date=April 2018}}

